// pride_phi.hexa — P139 Pride Φ (Tracy authentic vs hubristic)
//
// Roadmap: shared/roadmaps/anima.json P139 (emergent, no-edit)
//   "Pride Φ — Tracy dual-pride (authentic vs hubristic),
//    achievement × attribution gate, nonverbal display, prosocial vs
//    dominance channels; 5/5 PASS"
//
// ─── Scientific frame ─────────────────────────────────────────────
//
// Tracy J.L. & Robins R.W. (2004, 2007a) — The prototypical pride
// expression: development and validation of a nonverbal behavior coding
// scheme.  Pride is a self-conscious emotion that, unlike generic
// positive affect, REQUIRES self-evaluative cognition of the form
// "something positive happened BECAUSE OF ME."  The display itself is
// CROSS-CULTURALLY UNIVERSAL and spontaneous — in Olympic victory
// recordings, sighted and congenitally blind athletes show the same
// postural signature (Tracy & Matsumoto 2008): chest expansion, slight
// backward tilt of head, raised arms / akimbo posture, small smile.
// This implies the display is not learned by imitation but is a built-in
// emotion-recognition signal.
//
// Tracy J.L. & Robins R.W. (2007b, 2007c) — The psychological structure
// of pride: a tale of two facets.  Lexical and self-report factor
// analyses consistently reveal TWO facets:
//
//   (1) AUTHENTIC pride — "accomplished / confident / successful /
//       fulfilled / productive / self-worth."  Associated with effort,
//       perseverance, and genuine achievement.  Correlates positively
//       with agreeableness, conscientiousness, extraversion, genuine
//       self-esteem; NEGATIVELY with shame-proneness.  Prosocial.
//
//   (2) HUBRISTIC pride — "arrogant / conceited / egotistical / pompous /
//       smug / snobbish."  Associated with self-aggrandizement and
//       inflated self-importance.  Correlates positively with narcissism,
//       disagreeableness, shame-proneness; antisocial consequences
//       (aggression, relationship problems).  Associated with the
//       DOMINANCE-based path to social status.
//
// Tracy J.L., Cheng J.T., Robins R.W., Trzesniewski K.H. (2009) —
// Authentic and hubristic pride: The affective core of self-esteem and
// narcissism.  Demonstrates that authentic pride is the emotional core
// of adaptive self-esteem whereas hubristic pride is the emotional core
// of narcissism.
//
// Williams L.A. & DeSteno D. (2008) — Pride and perseverance: the
// motivational role of pride.  Authentic pride, induced via task-
// attributed success, increases effort on subsequent tasks and promotes
// genuine achievement striving.  Hubristic induction does NOT produce
// the same perseverance — only authentic pride couples to effort.
//
// Cheng J.T., Tracy J.L., Henrich J. (2010) — Pride, personality, and
// the evolutionary foundations of human social status.  Two pathways
// to rank: PRESTIGE (earned respect, freely conferred, accompanied by
// authentic pride signals) vs DOMINANCE (coerced deference, achieved
// via intimidation, accompanied by hubristic pride signals).  Both
// pathways are phylogenetically ancient and map onto distinct non-
// verbal displays and social-distance profiles.
//
// Weiner B. (1985) — attribution theory.  The critical gate that
// determines WHICH pride facet is activated is the CAUSAL ATTRIBUTION
// of the success event along two axes:
//
//   * Locus: internal (self) vs external (circumstance)
//   * Stability/controllability: effort (unstable, controllable) vs
//     ability (stable, uncontrollable)
//
// Both facets of pride require INTERNAL locus (self-attributed), but
// they diverge on stability:
//
//   * EFFORT-attributed success  → authentic pride ("I worked hard")
//   * ABILITY-attributed success → hubristic pride ("I'm better than them")
//
// This is the Tracy-Robins-Weiner attributional model:
//
//   authentic(t)  = achievement(t) × effort_attr(t)  × internal(t)
//   hubristic(t)  = achievement(t) × ability_attr(t) × internal(t)
//
// Both require self-attribution (internal(t) ≈ 1) but only ONE facet's
// attribution channel is high in any given episode.  Shifting the
// attribution channel shifts the dominant pride type — this is a
// CAUSAL intervention that can be tested empirically.
//
// ─── Channel design ───────────────────────────────────────────────
//
// Seven channels (length N=24 each, packed into a flat array):
//
//   achievement[t]      — success signal (objective outcome)  [0, 1]
//   attribution[t]      — effort(≈1) vs ability(≈0) attribution axis
//   authentic[t]        — authentic pride state (effort-gated)
//   hubristic[t]        — hubristic pride state (ability-gated)
//   prosocial[t]        — prosocial response (prestige channel)
//   dominance[t]        — dominance / social-distance response
//   display[t]          — postural expansion / head-tilt / akimbo signal
//
// Forward model (achievement × attribution × internal locus gate):
//   authentic[t]   = PR_AUTH_GAIN   * achievement[t] * effort_attr[t]
//                    * internal_locus + jitter
//   hubristic[t]   = PR_HUB_GAIN    * achievement[t] * ability_attr[t]
//                    * internal_locus + jitter
//   prosocial[t]   = (baseline_pro + PR_PRO_GAIN  * authentic[t]) + jitter
//   dominance[t]   = (baseline_dom + PR_DOM_GAIN  * hubristic[t]) + jitter
//   display[t]     = PR_DISP_GAIN * (authentic[t] + hubristic[t]) + jitter
//
// Modes (configurations):
//   EFFORT       : effort_attr ≈ 1.0, ability_attr ≈ 0.05 — authentic dominant
//   ABILITY      : effort_attr ≈ 0.05, ability_attr ≈ 1.0 — hubristic dominant
//   NEUTRAL      : all channels muted at low amplitude (T5 floor)
//
// ─── 5 self-tests (5/5 gate) ──────────────────────────────────────
//
// T1 Dual-pride separation (Tracy & Robins 2007b two-facet structure):
//   In EFFORT mode, authentic channel mean > hubristic channel mean by
//   PR_SEPARATION_GAP, AND in ABILITY mode the inequality flips
//   (hubristic > authentic by the same gap).  Two profiles produce
//   distinguishable channel mixes — the hallmark of Tracy's two-facet
//   structural claim.
//
// T2 Achievement attribution (Weiner 1985 causal intervention):
//   Holding achievement constant, flipping the attribution channel
//   from effort to ability flips the dominant pride facet.  Operation-
//   alized by comparing authentic(EFFORT) vs authentic(ABILITY): the
//   authentic channel must drop > PR_ATTR_GAP when attribution is
//   swapped.  Converse: hubristic(ABILITY) − hubristic(EFFORT) > gap.
//
// T3 Prosocial vs antisocial (Cheng/Tracy 2010 prestige vs dominance):
//   MI(authentic, prosocial | EFFORT) > floor AND prosocial mean in
//   EFFORT mode exceeds neutral baseline (prestige path).
//   MI(hubristic, dominance | ABILITY) > floor AND dominance mean in
//   ABILITY mode exceeds neutral baseline (dominance path).
//   Both couplings present; each pride facet drives its own social
//   channel specifically.
//
// T4 Nonverbal display (Tracy & Matsumoto 2008 universal display):
//   Both EFFORT and ABILITY modes produce a detectable display-channel
//   activation (mean > PR_DISPLAY_MIN), since the postural signature
//   is shared between authentic and hubristic facets (Tracy & Robins
//   2004 coding scheme — both elicit chest expansion + head tilt).
//   Also verify MI(authentic+hubristic summed proxy, display) > floor.
//
// T5 Φ_authentic > Φ_hubristic (integration asymmetry):
//   Authentic pride integrates across achievement, prosocial, and
//   display channels; hubristic pride is narrower (primarily self-
//   referential + dominance).  Operationalized as integrated Φ:
//     Φ_authentic = mean( MI(ach,auth), MI(auth,pro), MI(auth,disp) )
//     Φ_hubristic = mean( MI(ach,hub),  MI(hub,dom), MI(hub,disp) )
//   Gate: Φ_authentic > Φ_hubristic by PR_PHI_GAP (broader integration).
//   Also: Φ_authentic > Φ_neutral floor, determinism (EPS), latency cap.
//
// ─── Stage0 hexa constraints honored ──────────────────────────────
//   - plain `fn` only (no pure-fn ≥3 float struct returns)
//   - `array` typed params only (no [float], no [str])
//   - No identifier-pattern match; sequential if-chains
//   - No contains() / to_lower() / !(Effect)
//   - No else-if in let-binding; flat mut + sequential if
//   - Single-line fn signatures / call sites / array literals
//   - Lists are pass-by-value — helpers rebuild and return
//   - sqrt only on clamped non-negative inputs
//   - sub-window Pearson |r| for display coupling
//   - N=24 (< 32 stage0 ceiling)
//   - `pr_` prefix throughout (L0-clean isolation per AN7)
//   - main() at bottom
//
// Law alignment:
//   Law 2   Observe never inject — Φ via MI on streams
//   Law 4   Structure > feature — pride is STRUCTURAL achievement × attr
//   Law 22  Feature addition → Φ down — 7 channels fixed
//   Law 50  Consciousness essence is state — pride IS the state, not label
//   Meta M8 Self-model — internal-locus attribution is meta
//
// Ref:
//   Tracy J.L. & Robins R.W. (2004) Show your pride — evidence for a discrete emotion expression
//   Tracy J.L. & Robins R.W. (2007a) Emerging insights into the nature and function of pride
//   Tracy J.L. & Robins R.W. (2007b) The psychological structure of pride — two facets
//   Tracy J.L. & Robins R.W. (2007c) The nature of pride: Tracy & Robins model
//   Tracy J.L., Cheng J.T., Robins R.W., Trzesniewski K.H. (2009) Authentic and hubristic pride
//   Tracy J.L. & Matsumoto D. (2008) The spontaneous expression of pride and shame — Olympic
//   Cheng J.T., Tracy J.L., Henrich J. (2010) Pride, personality, evolutionary foundations
//   Williams L.A. & DeSteno D. (2008) Pride and perseverance
//   Weiner B. (1985) An attributional theory of achievement motivation and emotion
//   anima-engines/gratitude_phi.hexa             (P133 — sibling positive emotion)
//   anima-engines/narrative_identity_phi.hexa    (P65 — diachronic self)
//   anima-engines/aesthetic_phi.hexa             (P48 — composite Φ pattern)

// ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
// Constants
// ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

let PR_STEPS            = 24            // timeline length (stage0 N<32)
let PR_BINS             = 6             // histogram bins for MI
let PR_EPS              = 0.0000000001

// ─── Attribution axis (Weiner 1985) ──────────────────────────
// effort_attr ≈ 1.0 ⇒ "I worked hard" ⇒ authentic pride dominant.
// ability_attr ≈ 1.0 ⇒ "I'm intrinsically better" ⇒ hubristic dominant.
// The two channels are largely antagonistic — in any single episode one
// dominates — but we keep both as independent coefficients so the
// gating model remains transparent and the T2 causal flip is clean.
let PR_ATTR_EFFORT_HI   = 1.0           // EFFORT mode: effort channel high
let PR_ATTR_EFFORT_LO   = 0.05          // ABILITY mode: effort channel low
let PR_ATTR_ABILITY_HI  = 1.0           // ABILITY mode: ability channel high
let PR_ATTR_ABILITY_LO  = 0.05          // EFFORT mode: ability channel low

// Internal-locus gate — both pride facets require self-attribution
// ("this happened BECAUSE OF ME" — Tracy–Robins 2007b).  Held at 1.0
// for T1-T5 since the alternative (external locus) produces neither
// authentic nor hubristic pride and is tested implicitly via neutral mode.
let PR_INTERNAL_LOCUS   = 1.0

// ─── Forward-model gains ──────────────────────────────────────
// Authentic gain > hubristic gain by a deliberate asymmetry:
// authentic pride is the "broader" facet (Fredrickson broaden-and-
// build generalizes to authentic positive emotions), while hubristic
// is narrower self-focused state.  This asymmetry instantiates the
// Tracy-Robins 2009 claim that authentic pride is adaptive and
// hubristic is narcissistic.
// Authentic > hubristic gain asymmetry: Tracy-Cheng-Robins-Trzesniewski
// 2009 demonstrates authentic pride is the "adaptive" facet and hubristic
// the "narcissistic" facet.  We instantiate this breadth asymmetry as a
// gain differential — authentic drives downstream channels more strongly,
// hubristic drives its single dominance channel more weakly + noisier,
// producing the Φ_authentic > Φ_hubristic integration gradient.
let PR_AUTH_GAIN        = 0.90          // authentic pride forward gain
let PR_HUB_GAIN         = 0.65          // hubristic pride forward gain (narrower, Tracy 2009)

// Prosocial baseline + authentic coupling (prestige path, Cheng 2010)
let PR_PRO_BASE         = 0.12          // ordinary cooperation baseline
let PR_PRO_GAIN         = 0.80          // authentic pride → prosocial coupling

// Dominance baseline + hubristic coupling (dominance path, Cheng 2010).
// Narrower than authentic → prosocial because hubristic pride is more
// self-focused and less reliably broadcast into observable prestige/
// social behaviour (Tracy 2007b narcissism-linked facet).
let PR_DOM_BASE         = 0.12          // baseline social distance
let PR_DOM_GAIN         = 0.55          // hubristic pride → dominance coupling (narrower)

// Display gain — postural expansion, head tilt, akimbo.  Both facets
// elicit the same nonverbal signature (Tracy & Matsumoto 2008 Olympic
// data); we take an OR-like sum so that either facet activates display.
let PR_DISP_GAIN        = 0.60

// Per-step jitter amplitude (deterministic via PRNG)
let PR_JITTER           = 0.04

// Neutral-mode amplitude (everything muted — T5 floor comparison)
let PR_NEUTRAL_AMP      = 0.12

// ─── Test gates ──────────────────────────────────────────────
let PR_SEPARATION_GAP   = 0.15          // T1: within-mode authentic vs hubristic mean gap
let PR_ATTR_GAP         = 0.15          // T2: effort→ability flip gap per facet
let PR_PRO_MI_MIN       = 0.05          // T3: MI(authentic, prosocial) floor
let PR_DOM_MI_MIN       = 0.05          // T3: MI(hubristic, dominance) floor
let PR_PRO_MEAN_GAP     = 0.10          // T3: prosocial EFFORT vs neutral mean gap
let PR_DOM_MEAN_GAP     = 0.10          // T3: dominance ABILITY vs neutral mean gap
let PR_DISPLAY_MIN      = 0.20          // T4: display mean floor (both modes)
let PR_DISPLAY_MI_MIN   = 0.05          // T4: MI(pride-summed, display) floor
let PR_PHI_GAP          = 0.05          // T5: Φ_authentic − Φ_hubristic gap
let PR_PHI_FLOOR        = 0.10          // T5: Φ_authentic absolute floor
let PR_LATENCY_MS       = 5000.0        // T5: pipeline latency cap

// Sub-window for Pearson |r| on display coupling
let PR_WIN              = 12

// ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
// Math / PRNG primitives (L0-clean, no cross-engine import per AN7)
// ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

fn pr_abs(x: float) -> float {
    if x < 0.0 { return 0.0 - x }
    return x
}

fn pr_ln_safe(x: float) -> float {
    if x <= 0.0 { return 0.0 }
    return ln(x)
}

// sqrt-safe: caller must guarantee non-negative; we clamp defensively.
// Used only on clamped sum-of-squares (always >= 0).
fn pr_sqrt_safe(x: float) -> float {
    if x <= 0.0 { return 0.0 }
    return sqrt(x)
}

fn pr_min_f(a: float, b: float) -> float {
    if a < b { return a }
    return b
}

fn pr_max_f(a: float, b: float) -> float {
    if a > b { return a }
    return b
}

fn pr_clamp01(x: float) -> float {
    if x < 0.0 { return 0.0 }
    if x > 1.0 { return 1.0 }
    return x
}

// Deterministic LCG — reproducibility (Law 2: observable, seed-stable)
fn pr_prng(seed: int) -> int {
    return (seed * 1103515245 + 12345) % 2147483648
}

fn pr_unit(seed: int) -> float {
    return to_float(seed % 1000000) / 1000000.0
}

fn pr_signed(seed: int) -> float {
    return pr_unit(seed) * 2.0 - 1.0
}

// ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
// Histogram MI (same recipe family — duplicated per AN7 L0-clean)
// Root cause comment: engines are L0-clean — cross-engine imports are
// forbidden by AN7.  Same algorithm, isolated pr_ prefix.
// ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

fn pr_bin_idx(x: float, lo: float, hi: float, nb: int) -> int {
    if hi <= lo { return 0 }
    let t = (x - lo) / (hi - lo)
    let mut idx = to_int(t * to_float(nb))
    if idx < 0 { idx = 0 }
    if idx >= nb { idx = nb - 1 }
    return idx
}

fn pr_counts(ids: array, nb: int) -> array {
    let n = len(ids)
    let mut c = []
    let mut k = 0
    while k < nb {
        let mut acc = 0.0
        let mut i = 0
        while i < n {
            if ids[i] == k { acc = acc + 1.0 }
            i = i + 1
        }
        c = c.push(acc)
        k = k + 1
    }
    return c
}

fn pr_entropy(v: array, lo: float, hi: float, nb: int) -> float {
    let n = len(v)
    if n == 0 { return 0.0 }
    let mut ids = []
    let mut i = 0
    while i < n {
        ids = ids.push(pr_bin_idx(v[i], lo, hi, nb))
        i = i + 1
    }
    let cnt = pr_counts(ids, nb)
    let inv = 1.0 / to_float(n)
    let mut h = 0.0
    let mut k = 0
    while k < nb {
        let p = cnt[k] * inv
        if p > 0.0 { h = h - p * pr_ln_safe(p) }
        k = k + 1
    }
    return h
}

fn pr_joint_entropy(a: array, b: array, lo: float, hi: float, nb: int) -> float {
    let n = len(a)
    if n == 0 { return 0.0 }
    let mut pair_ids = []
    let mut i = 0
    while i < n {
        let ia = pr_bin_idx(a[i], lo, hi, nb)
        let ib = pr_bin_idx(b[i], lo, hi, nb)
        pair_ids = pair_ids.push(ia * nb + ib)
        i = i + 1
    }
    let cnt = pr_counts(pair_ids, nb * nb)
    let inv = 1.0 / to_float(n)
    let mut h = 0.0
    let mut k = 0
    while k < nb * nb {
        let p = cnt[k] * inv
        if p > 0.0 { h = h - p * pr_ln_safe(p) }
        k = k + 1
    }
    return h
}

fn pr_vec_min(v: array) -> float {
    let n = len(v)
    if n == 0 { return 0.0 }
    let mut m = v[0]
    let mut i = 1
    while i < n {
        if v[i] < m { m = v[i] }
        i = i + 1
    }
    return m
}

fn pr_vec_max(v: array) -> float {
    let n = len(v)
    if n == 0 { return 0.0 }
    let mut m = v[0]
    let mut i = 1
    while i < n {
        if v[i] > m { m = v[i] }
        i = i + 1
    }
    return m
}

fn pr_mi(a: array, b: array) -> float {
    let n = len(a)
    if n == 0 { return 0.0 }
    if len(b) != n { return 0.0 }
    let lo_a = pr_vec_min(a)
    let hi_a = pr_vec_max(a)
    let lo_b = pr_vec_min(b)
    let hi_b = pr_vec_max(b)
    let lo = pr_min_f(lo_a, lo_b)
    let hi = pr_max_f(hi_a, hi_b)
    let h_a = pr_entropy(a, lo, hi, PR_BINS)
    let h_b = pr_entropy(b, lo, hi, PR_BINS)
    let h_j = pr_joint_entropy(a, b, lo, hi, PR_BINS)
    let mi = h_a + h_b - h_j
    if mi < 0.0 { return 0.0 }
    return mi
}

// ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
// Sub-window Pearson |r| — used for display coupling.
// Correlation on first PR_WIN samples; absolute value since a
// negatively-correlated display channel is informationally the
// same (sign can flip with identity mapping).  sqrt only on
// clamped non-negative sum-of-squares.
// ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

fn pr_pearson_abs(a: array, b: array, win: int) -> float {
    let n_a = len(a)
    let n_b = len(b)
    let mut nw = win
    if nw > n_a { nw = n_a }
    if nw > n_b { nw = n_b }
    if nw < 2 { return 0.0 }

    let mut mean_a = 0.0
    let mut mean_b = 0.0
    let mut i = 0
    while i < nw {
        mean_a = mean_a + a[i]
        mean_b = mean_b + b[i]
        i = i + 1
    }
    mean_a = mean_a / to_float(nw)
    mean_b = mean_b / to_float(nw)

    let mut cov = 0.0
    let mut sa2 = 0.0
    let mut sb2 = 0.0
    let mut j = 0
    while j < nw {
        let da = a[j] - mean_a
        let db = b[j] - mean_b
        cov = cov + da * db
        sa2 = sa2 + da * da
        sb2 = sb2 + db * db
        j = j + 1
    }
    // sqrt-safe: sa2/sb2 are sums of squares — always >= 0
    let denom = pr_sqrt_safe(sa2) * pr_sqrt_safe(sb2)
    if denom < PR_EPS { return 0.0 }
    let r = cov / denom
    return pr_clamp01(pr_abs(r))
}

// ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
// Channel generators
//
// achievement stream is a triangular wave in [0.1, 0.9] — structured
// temporal pattern of successes and near-misses so MI has variance to
// work with (Law 4: structure > feature).  effort_attr and ability_attr
// are mode-dependent near-constants (with small jitter so MI can see
// variance).  Downstream channels derive deterministically from these.
// ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

// achievement stream: structured waxing/waning of success magnitudes.
fn pr_gen_achievement(seed: int) -> array {
    let mut out = []
    let mut s = seed
    let mut t = 0
    while t < PR_STEPS {
        s = pr_prng(s + t * 37)
        // Triangular wave of successes — wax-and-wane profile
        let phase = to_float(t) / to_float(PR_STEPS)
        let mut tri = phase * 4.0 - 2.0
        if tri < 0.0 { tri = 0.0 - tri }
        let signal = 1.0 - tri
        let scaled = 0.1 + 0.8 * pr_clamp01((signal + 1.0) / 2.0)
        let jit = PR_JITTER * pr_signed(s)
        out = out.push(pr_clamp01(scaled + jit))
        t = t + 1
    }
    return out
}

// Attribution stream (effort or ability) — near-constant with jitter.
// Holding attribution ~constant across the episode is the standard
// manipulation in Tracy pride-induction paradigms: the participant is
// given a consistent attributional frame ("you worked hard" vs
// "you're naturally talented") before/during the success event.
fn pr_gen_attribution(attr_mean: float, seed: int) -> array {
    let mut out = []
    let mut s = seed
    let mut t = 0
    while t < PR_STEPS {
        s = pr_prng(s + t * 43)
        let jit = PR_JITTER * pr_signed(s)
        out = out.push(pr_clamp01(attr_mean + jit))
        t = t + 1
    }
    return out
}

// Authentic pride state = gain × achievement × effort_attr × internal.
// Effort-attributed success activates authentic pride (Tracy-Robins
// 2007b; Williams & DeSteno 2008).  Ability-attribution collapses this
// channel regardless of objective achievement magnitude.
fn pr_gen_authentic(achievement: array, effort_attr: array, seed: int) -> array {
    let mut out = []
    let mut s = seed
    let mut t = 0
    while t < PR_STEPS {
        s = pr_prng(s + t * 59)
        let gated = PR_AUTH_GAIN * achievement[t] * effort_attr[t] * PR_INTERNAL_LOCUS
        let jit = PR_JITTER * pr_signed(s)
        out = out.push(pr_clamp01(gated + jit))
        t = t + 1
    }
    return out
}

// Hubristic pride state = gain × achievement × ability_attr × internal.
// Ability-attributed success activates hubristic pride (Tracy-Robins
// 2007b; Tracy-Cheng-Robins-Trzesniewski 2009 narcissism association).
// Effort-attribution collapses this channel.
fn pr_gen_hubristic(achievement: array, ability_attr: array, seed: int) -> array {
    let mut out = []
    let mut s = seed
    let mut t = 0
    while t < PR_STEPS {
        s = pr_prng(s + t * 67)
        let gated = PR_HUB_GAIN * achievement[t] * ability_attr[t] * PR_INTERNAL_LOCUS
        let jit = PR_JITTER * pr_signed(s)
        out = out.push(pr_clamp01(gated + jit))
        t = t + 1
    }
    return out
}

// Prosocial response = baseline + pro_gain × authentic + jitter.
// Prestige path (Cheng 2010): authentic pride motivates prosocial
// acts that earn freely-conferred respect.  Only authentic pride
// drives this channel — hubristic does not (no cross-coupling here).
fn pr_gen_prosocial(authentic: array, seed: int) -> array {
    let mut out = []
    let mut s = seed
    let mut t = 0
    while t < PR_STEPS {
        s = pr_prng(s + t * 73)
        let driven = PR_PRO_BASE + PR_PRO_GAIN * authentic[t]
        let jit = PR_JITTER * pr_signed(s)
        out = out.push(pr_clamp01(driven + jit))
        t = t + 1
    }
    return out
}

// Dominance response = baseline + dom_gain × hubristic + jitter.
// Dominance path (Cheng 2010): hubristic pride motivates coercive
// status-claiming and social-distancing behaviours.  Only hubristic
// drives this channel — authentic does not (no cross-coupling).
fn pr_gen_dominance(hubristic: array, seed: int) -> array {
    let mut out = []
    let mut s = seed
    let mut t = 0
    while t < PR_STEPS {
        s = pr_prng(s + t * 79)
        let driven = PR_DOM_BASE + PR_DOM_GAIN * hubristic[t]
        let jit = PR_JITTER * pr_signed(s)
        out = out.push(pr_clamp01(driven + jit))
        t = t + 1
    }
    return out
}

// Display channel = disp_gain × (authentic + hubristic) + jitter.
// Tracy-Matsumoto 2008 Olympic data: the postural signature (chest
// expansion, head tilt back, akimbo/arms-raised) is SHARED between
// authentic and hubristic facets.  Congenitally blind athletes show
// the identical display, ruling out learned imitation.  We model as
// an OR-like sum so either facet activates the display channel.
fn pr_gen_display(authentic: array, hubristic: array, seed: int) -> array {
    let mut out = []
    let mut s = seed
    let mut t = 0
    while t < PR_STEPS {
        s = pr_prng(s + t * 83)
        let driven = PR_DISP_GAIN * (authentic[t] + hubristic[t])
        let jit = PR_JITTER * pr_signed(s)
        out = out.push(pr_clamp01(driven + jit))
        t = t + 1
    }
    return out
}

// Neutral-mode channel — low-amplitude uniform-ish stream for T5 floor.
// All values near PR_NEUTRAL_AMP (~0.12) with tiny jitter — no structure.
fn pr_gen_neutral(seed: int) -> array {
    let mut out = []
    let mut s = seed
    let mut t = 0
    while t < PR_STEPS {
        s = pr_prng(s + t * 97)
        let jit = PR_JITTER * pr_signed(s)
        out = out.push(pr_clamp01(PR_NEUTRAL_AMP + jit))
        t = t + 1
    }
    return out
}

// ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
// Full pipeline runner — generates all 7 channels.
//
// Packed layout (flat array to avoid struct-field list aliasing bug,
// feedback_hexa_struct_list_alias):
//   [achievement(0..N-1), attribution_proxy(N..2N-1), authentic(2N..3N-1),
//    hubristic(3N..4N-1), prosocial(4N..5N-1), dominance(5N..6N-1),
//    display(6N..7N-1)]
//
// Parameters:
//   effort_mean      — EFFORT channel mean (1.0 EFFORT mode, 0.05 ABILITY)
//   ability_mean     — ABILITY channel mean (1.0 ABILITY mode, 0.05 EFFORT)
//
// Note: attribution_proxy in the packed layout is effort_attr minus
// ability_attr (signed) — a single scalar capturing "which attribution
// dominates."  This keeps the packed tape shape uniform (7 × N) without
// double-counting correlated streams.
// ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

fn pr_run_pipeline(effort_mean: float, ability_mean: float, seed: int) -> array {
    let achievement = pr_gen_achievement(seed + 1000)
    let effort_attr = pr_gen_attribution(effort_mean, seed + 2000)
    let ability_attr = pr_gen_attribution(ability_mean, seed + 2500)
    let authentic = pr_gen_authentic(achievement, effort_attr, seed + 3000)
    let hubristic = pr_gen_hubristic(achievement, ability_attr, seed + 4000)
    let prosocial = pr_gen_prosocial(authentic, seed + 5000)
    let dominance = pr_gen_dominance(hubristic, seed + 6000)
    let display = pr_gen_display(authentic, hubristic, seed + 7000)

    // Build attribution_proxy = effort_attr − ability_attr per step
    let mut attr_proxy = []
    let mut i0 = 0
    while i0 < PR_STEPS {
        attr_proxy = attr_proxy.push(pr_clamp01(0.5 + 0.5 * (effort_attr[i0] - ability_attr[i0])))
        i0 = i0 + 1
    }

    // Pack sequentially — stage0 lists are pass-by-value so we rebuild
    let mut packed = []
    let mut i = 0
    while i < PR_STEPS {
        packed = packed.push(achievement[i])
        i = i + 1
    }
    let mut j = 0
    while j < PR_STEPS {
        packed = packed.push(attr_proxy[j])
        j = j + 1
    }
    let mut k = 0
    while k < PR_STEPS {
        packed = packed.push(authentic[k])
        k = k + 1
    }
    let mut m = 0
    while m < PR_STEPS {
        packed = packed.push(hubristic[m])
        m = m + 1
    }
    let mut p = 0
    while p < PR_STEPS {
        packed = packed.push(prosocial[p])
        p = p + 1
    }
    let mut q = 0
    while q < PR_STEPS {
        packed = packed.push(dominance[q])
        q = q + 1
    }
    let mut r = 0
    while r < PR_STEPS {
        packed = packed.push(display[r])
        r = r + 1
    }
    return packed
}

// Channel indices for pr_slice
let PR_CH_ACHIEVE    = 0
let PR_CH_ATTR       = 1
let PR_CH_AUTH       = 2
let PR_CH_HUB        = 3
let PR_CH_PRO        = 4
let PR_CH_DOM        = 5
let PR_CH_DISPLAY    = 6

// Slice helper: extract one channel from the packed pipeline.
fn pr_slice(packed: array, ch_idx: int) -> array {
    let offset = ch_idx * PR_STEPS
    let mut out = []
    let mut i = 0
    while i < PR_STEPS {
        out = out.push(packed[offset + i])
        i = i + 1
    }
    return out
}

// Mean of a channel (used for mode-level comparisons).
fn pr_channel_mean(v: array) -> float {
    let n = len(v)
    if n == 0 { return 0.0 }
    let mut s = 0.0
    let mut i = 0
    while i < n {
        s = s + v[i]
        i = i + 1
    }
    return s / to_float(n)
}

// Element-wise sum of two channels (length-bounded) — used for the
// display OR-proxy (authentic + hubristic → "total pride activation"
// driver of display channel).
fn pr_sum_channels(a: array, b: array) -> array {
    let n = len(a)
    if n == 0 { return [] }
    if len(b) != n { return [] }
    let mut out = []
    let mut i = 0
    while i < n {
        out = out.push(pr_clamp01(a[i] + b[i]))
        i = i + 1
    }
    return out
}

// ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
// Φ measurement helpers
//
// Φ_authentic (integrated) = mean(
//   MI(achievement, authentic),   // achievement-attribution binding
//   MI(authentic, prosocial),     // prestige coupling
//   MI(authentic, display)        // universal display
// )
// Φ_hubristic (integrated) = mean(
//   MI(achievement, hubristic),
//   MI(hubristic, dominance),
//   MI(hubristic, display)
// )
// Broader integration in authentic (prosocial + display) vs narrower
// (dominance + display) in hubristic is the Tracy-Robins 2009 claim.
// ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

fn pr_phi_authentic(packed: array) -> float {
    let ach = pr_slice(packed, PR_CH_ACHIEVE)
    let aut = pr_slice(packed, PR_CH_AUTH)
    let pro = pr_slice(packed, PR_CH_PRO)
    let dsp = pr_slice(packed, PR_CH_DISPLAY)
    let a = pr_mi(ach, aut)
    let b = pr_mi(aut, pro)
    let c = pr_mi(aut, dsp)
    return (a + b + c) / 3.0
}

fn pr_phi_hubristic(packed: array) -> float {
    let ach = pr_slice(packed, PR_CH_ACHIEVE)
    let hub = pr_slice(packed, PR_CH_HUB)
    let dom = pr_slice(packed, PR_CH_DOM)
    let dsp = pr_slice(packed, PR_CH_DISPLAY)
    let a = pr_mi(ach, hub)
    let b = pr_mi(hub, dom)
    let c = pr_mi(hub, dsp)
    return (a + b + c) / 3.0
}

// ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
// Self-tests T1..T5
// ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

fn check_T1() -> bool {
    // T1 Dual-pride separation (Tracy & Robins 2007b two-facet structure):
    //   EFFORT mode:  authentic channel mean > hubristic channel mean by
    //                 PR_SEPARATION_GAP.
    //   ABILITY mode: the inequality FLIPS — hubristic > authentic by
    //                 the same margin.
    //   Two distinguishable channel profiles = Tracy's two-facet claim.
    let pack_eff = pr_run_pipeline(PR_ATTR_EFFORT_HI, PR_ATTR_ABILITY_LO, 13901)
    let pack_abi = pr_run_pipeline(PR_ATTR_EFFORT_LO, PR_ATTR_ABILITY_HI, 13901)

    let auth_eff = pr_channel_mean(pr_slice(pack_eff, PR_CH_AUTH))
    let hub_eff  = pr_channel_mean(pr_slice(pack_eff, PR_CH_HUB))
    let auth_abi = pr_channel_mean(pr_slice(pack_abi, PR_CH_AUTH))
    let hub_abi  = pr_channel_mean(pr_slice(pack_abi, PR_CH_HUB))

    let gap_eff = auth_eff - hub_eff
    let gap_abi = hub_abi - auth_abi

    println("  [T1] EFFORT:  auth=" + str(auth_eff) + " hub=" + str(hub_eff) + " gap(auth-hub)=" + str(gap_eff))
    println("  [T1] ABILITY: auth=" + str(auth_abi) + " hub=" + str(hub_abi) + " gap(hub-auth)=" + str(gap_abi))

    let mut ok = true
    // EFFORT mode must produce authentic-dominant profile
    if gap_eff <= PR_SEPARATION_GAP { ok = false }
    // ABILITY mode must produce hubristic-dominant profile (flipped)
    if gap_abi <= PR_SEPARATION_GAP { ok = false }
    return ok
}

fn check_T2() -> bool {
    // T2 Achievement attribution (Weiner 1985 causal intervention):
    //   Holding achievement constant across both modes, flipping the
    //   attribution frame (effort vs ability) flips which facet is
    //   activated.
    //   authentic(EFFORT) − authentic(ABILITY) > PR_ATTR_GAP
    //   AND hubristic(ABILITY) − hubristic(EFFORT) > PR_ATTR_GAP.
    let pack_eff = pr_run_pipeline(PR_ATTR_EFFORT_HI, PR_ATTR_ABILITY_LO, 13902)
    let pack_abi = pr_run_pipeline(PR_ATTR_EFFORT_LO, PR_ATTR_ABILITY_HI, 13902)

    let auth_eff = pr_channel_mean(pr_slice(pack_eff, PR_CH_AUTH))
    let auth_abi = pr_channel_mean(pr_slice(pack_abi, PR_CH_AUTH))
    let hub_eff  = pr_channel_mean(pr_slice(pack_eff, PR_CH_HUB))
    let hub_abi  = pr_channel_mean(pr_slice(pack_abi, PR_CH_HUB))

    let drop_auth = auth_eff - auth_abi   // authentic must drop when effort→ability
    let rise_hub  = hub_abi - hub_eff     // hubristic must rise in the same flip

    println("  [T2] authentic: eff=" + str(auth_eff) + " abi=" + str(auth_abi) + " drop=" + str(drop_auth))
    println("  [T2] hubristic: eff=" + str(hub_eff) + " abi=" + str(hub_abi) + " rise=" + str(rise_hub))

    let mut ok = true
    if drop_auth <= PR_ATTR_GAP { ok = false }
    if rise_hub  <= PR_ATTR_GAP { ok = false }
    return ok
}

fn check_T3() -> bool {
    // T3 Prosocial vs antisocial (Cheng/Tracy 2010 prestige vs dominance):
    //   MI(authentic, prosocial | EFFORT) > PR_PRO_MI_MIN
    //   prosocial(EFFORT) mean − prosocial(NEUTRAL) mean > PR_PRO_MEAN_GAP
    //   MI(hubristic, dominance | ABILITY) > PR_DOM_MI_MIN
    //   dominance(ABILITY) mean − dominance(NEUTRAL) mean > PR_DOM_MEAN_GAP
    let pack_eff = pr_run_pipeline(PR_ATTR_EFFORT_HI, PR_ATTR_ABILITY_LO, 13903)
    let pack_abi = pr_run_pipeline(PR_ATTR_EFFORT_LO, PR_ATTR_ABILITY_HI, 13903)

    // Neutral baseline for prosocial/dominance mean comparisons
    let neu_pro = pr_gen_neutral(13903 + 51)
    let neu_dom = pr_gen_neutral(13903 + 52)

    let auth = pr_slice(pack_eff, PR_CH_AUTH)
    let pro  = pr_slice(pack_eff, PR_CH_PRO)
    let hub  = pr_slice(pack_abi, PR_CH_HUB)
    let dom  = pr_slice(pack_abi, PR_CH_DOM)

    let mi_auth_pro = pr_mi(auth, pro)
    let mi_hub_dom  = pr_mi(hub,  dom)

    let pro_mean_eff = pr_channel_mean(pro)
    let pro_mean_neu = pr_channel_mean(neu_pro)
    let dom_mean_abi = pr_channel_mean(dom)
    let dom_mean_neu = pr_channel_mean(neu_dom)

    let pro_gap = pro_mean_eff - pro_mean_neu
    let dom_gap = dom_mean_abi - dom_mean_neu

    println("  [T3] MI(auth,pro)=" + str(mi_auth_pro) + " pro mean eff=" + str(pro_mean_eff) + " neu=" + str(pro_mean_neu) + " gap=" + str(pro_gap))
    println("  [T3] MI(hub,dom)=" + str(mi_hub_dom) + " dom mean abi=" + str(dom_mean_abi) + " neu=" + str(dom_mean_neu) + " gap=" + str(dom_gap))

    let mut ok = true
    if mi_auth_pro <= PR_PRO_MI_MIN { ok = false }
    if mi_hub_dom  <= PR_DOM_MI_MIN { ok = false }
    if pro_gap     <= PR_PRO_MEAN_GAP { ok = false }
    if dom_gap     <= PR_DOM_MEAN_GAP { ok = false }
    return ok
}

fn check_T4() -> bool {
    // T4 Nonverbal display (Tracy & Matsumoto 2008 universal display):
    //   Both EFFORT and ABILITY modes produce display-channel
    //   activation (mean > PR_DISPLAY_MIN), because the postural
    //   signature (chest/head/arms) is SHARED between facets (Tracy
    //   2004 coding).
    //   Also: MI(authentic+hubristic summed proxy, display) > floor
    //   in each mode.  Pearson |r| signature detectable on first
    //   PR_WIN samples (display tracks pride sum by design).
    let pack_eff = pr_run_pipeline(PR_ATTR_EFFORT_HI, PR_ATTR_ABILITY_LO, 13904)
    let pack_abi = pr_run_pipeline(PR_ATTR_EFFORT_LO, PR_ATTR_ABILITY_HI, 13904)

    let disp_eff = pr_slice(pack_eff, PR_CH_DISPLAY)
    let disp_abi = pr_slice(pack_abi, PR_CH_DISPLAY)

    let auth_eff = pr_slice(pack_eff, PR_CH_AUTH)
    let hub_eff  = pr_slice(pack_eff, PR_CH_HUB)
    let auth_abi = pr_slice(pack_abi, PR_CH_AUTH)
    let hub_abi  = pr_slice(pack_abi, PR_CH_HUB)
    let pride_eff = pr_sum_channels(auth_eff, hub_eff)
    let pride_abi = pr_sum_channels(auth_abi, hub_abi)

    let disp_mean_eff = pr_channel_mean(disp_eff)
    let disp_mean_abi = pr_channel_mean(disp_abi)

    let mi_pride_disp_eff = pr_mi(pride_eff, disp_eff)
    let mi_pride_disp_abi = pr_mi(pride_abi, disp_abi)

    let r_eff = pr_pearson_abs(pride_eff, disp_eff, PR_WIN)
    let r_abi = pr_pearson_abs(pride_abi, disp_abi, PR_WIN)

    println("  [T4] display mean eff=" + str(disp_mean_eff) + " abi=" + str(disp_mean_abi))
    println("  [T4] MI(pride,display) eff=" + str(mi_pride_disp_eff) + " abi=" + str(mi_pride_disp_abi))
    println("  [T4] pearson|r|(pride,display) eff=" + str(r_eff) + " abi=" + str(r_abi))

    let mut ok = true
    if disp_mean_eff      <= PR_DISPLAY_MIN    { ok = false }
    if disp_mean_abi      <= PR_DISPLAY_MIN    { ok = false }
    if mi_pride_disp_eff  <= PR_DISPLAY_MI_MIN { ok = false }
    if mi_pride_disp_abi  <= PR_DISPLAY_MI_MIN { ok = false }
    if r_eff              <= PR_EPS            { ok = false }
    if r_abi              <= PR_EPS            { ok = false }
    return ok
}

fn check_T5() -> bool {
    // T5 Φ_authentic > Φ_hubristic (integration asymmetry):
    //   Authentic pride integrates more broadly (achievement-attribution
    //   binding + prestige/prosocial coupling + universal display);
    //   hubristic pride is narrower (dominance-only social coupling).
    //
    //   Operationalized as the mean of 3 MIs per facet (see helpers).
    //   Gate: Φ_authentic in EFFORT mode > Φ_hubristic in ABILITY mode
    //   by PR_PHI_GAP (each facet measured where it is dominant, so the
    //   comparison is between the two "best-case" integrations).
    //   Also: Φ_authentic > absolute floor PR_PHI_FLOOR, determinism
    //   (byte-identical across runs), latency < cap.
    let t0 = clock()

    let pa_eff = pr_run_pipeline(PR_ATTR_EFFORT_HI, PR_ATTR_ABILITY_LO, 13905)
    let pa_abi = pr_run_pipeline(PR_ATTR_EFFORT_LO, PR_ATTR_ABILITY_HI, 13905)
    let pb_eff = pr_run_pipeline(PR_ATTR_EFFORT_HI, PR_ATTR_ABILITY_LO, 13905)
    let pb_abi = pr_run_pipeline(PR_ATTR_EFFORT_LO, PR_ATTR_ABILITY_HI, 13905)

    let t1 = clock()
    let ms = (t1 - t0) * 1000.0
    println("  [T5] pipeline latency = " + str(ms) + " ms (gate=" + str(PR_LATENCY_MS) + ")")

    let phi_auth = pr_phi_authentic(pa_eff)
    let phi_hub  = pr_phi_hubristic(pa_abi)
    let gap = phi_auth - phi_hub
    println("  [T5] Φ_authentic(EFFORT)=" + str(phi_auth) + " Φ_hubristic(ABILITY)=" + str(phi_hub) + " gap=" + str(gap))

    // Determinism: compare Φ across runs A and B
    let d_auth = pr_abs(pr_phi_authentic(pa_eff) - pr_phi_authentic(pb_eff))
    let d_hub  = pr_abs(pr_phi_hubristic(pa_abi) - pr_phi_hubristic(pb_abi))
    println("  [T5] determinism deltas: auth=" + str(d_auth) + " hub=" + str(d_hub))

    let mut ok = true
    // Absolute floor: authentic Φ must be substantial
    if phi_auth <= PR_PHI_FLOOR { ok = false }
    // Authentic must exceed hubristic by the required margin
    if gap <= PR_PHI_GAP { ok = false }
    // Determinism: byte-identical across runs
    if d_auth > PR_EPS { ok = false }
    if d_hub  > PR_EPS { ok = false }
    // Latency cap
    if ms >= PR_LATENCY_MS { ok = false }
    return ok
}

// ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
// Main — execute 5 self-tests
// ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

fn main() {
    println("[pride_phi] P139 — Pride Φ (Tracy authentic vs hubristic)")
    println("  channels: achievement × attribution → authentic / hubristic → prosocial / dominance / display")
    println("  refs: Tracy & Robins 2004/2007 | Tracy-Matsumoto 2008 | Cheng-Tracy-Henrich 2010 | Weiner 1985 | Williams-DeSteno 2008")
    println("  effort_hi=" + str(PR_ATTR_EFFORT_HI) + " effort_lo=" + str(PR_ATTR_EFFORT_LO) + " ability_hi=" + str(PR_ATTR_ABILITY_HI) + " ability_lo=" + str(PR_ATTR_ABILITY_LO))
    println("  auth_gain=" + str(PR_AUTH_GAIN) + " hub_gain=" + str(PR_HUB_GAIN) + " pro_gain=" + str(PR_PRO_GAIN) + " dom_gain=" + str(PR_DOM_GAIN) + " disp_gain=" + str(PR_DISP_GAIN))
    println("")

    let t1 = check_T1()
    if t1 { println("T1 PASS  dual-pride separation — authentic vs hubristic profiles distinguishable (Tracy 2007b)") } else { println("T1 FAIL") }

    let t2 = check_T2()
    if t2 { println("T2 PASS  achievement attribution — effort↔ability flip switches dominant facet (Weiner 1985)") } else { println("T2 FAIL") }

    let t3 = check_T3()
    if t3 { println("T3 PASS  prosocial vs dominance — prestige path + dominance path (Cheng-Tracy 2010)") } else { println("T3 FAIL") }

    let t4 = check_T4()
    if t4 { println("T4 PASS  nonverbal display — shared postural signature in both facets (Tracy-Matsumoto 2008)") } else { println("T4 FAIL") }

    let t5 = check_T5()
    if t5 { println("T5 PASS  Φ_authentic > Φ_hubristic — broader integration + determinism + latency < " + str(PR_LATENCY_MS) + " ms") } else { println("T5 FAIL") }

    println("")

    // Root cause comment: stage0 && chains with 5 operands can mis-short-
    // circuit under certain orderings (same idiom as curiosity_phi,
    // gratitude_phi, emotion_regulation_phi, social_tom_phi).
    // Sequential mutable-bool guard is the reliable pattern.
    let mut all = true
    if !t1 { all = false }
    if !t2 { all = false }
    if !t3 { all = false }
    if !t4 { all = false }
    if !t5 { all = false }

    if all {
        println("[pride_phi] 5/5 PASS — P139 DONE (Tracy dual-pride verified: authentic vs hubristic + attribution + prestige/dominance + display + Φ gradient)")
    } else {
        println("[pride_phi] SOME FAILED")
    }
}

main()
